comments.text:
There's quite a few similar words. Underbart to wunderbar, lustig to 
lustig, hallå and hallo, äckel and ekel, and many more. They both are 
Germanic languages, and therefore have many cognates (similar words with 
similar meanings). If you know one language fluently, learning the other 
would be quite a lot easier. There's many similarities between the two. 
Numbers, too. Sex and sechs, for example. There's obviously more, but I'll 
leave it at that =P

comments.text:
Well, German and Swedish share a common root in terms of language. Both 
derive from the language from the Aryan's of India. German is a version of 
the Germanic language that was spoken in the Gauls and Norsemen that 
invaded Europe in the early Dark Ages, the end of the Roman Empire. So 
Swedish and German share a common root and many of the words and meanings 
are similar. But unfortunately German evolved while Swedish did not, 
resulting in Swedish being the more rough and coarse language.
